    <!-- http://example.org/mathkg/gloss/IsometricEmbedding -->

    <owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="http://example.org/mathkg/gloss/IsometricEmbedding">
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://example.org/mathkg/GlossRecord"/>
        <glossForConcept rdf:resource="http://example.org/mathkg/Isometricembedding"/>
        <canonicalGloss>Isometric embedding: Let $(M,g)$ and $(N,h)$ be Riemannian manifolds. An isometric embedding is a smooth embedding $f : M \\to N$ which preserves the metric in the sense that $g$ is equal to the pullback of $h$ by $f$, i.e. $g = f*h$.</canonicalGloss>
        <conciseForm>Isometric embedding: Let $(M,g)$ and $(N,h)$ be Riemannian manifolds. An isometric embedding is a smooth embedding $f : M \\to N$ which preserves the metric in the sense that $g$ is equal to the pullback of $h$ by $f$, i.e. $g = f*h$.</conciseForm>
        <documentRoleForm>In a mathematical document, isometric embedding usually signals a scalar concept with provenance from OntoMathPRO.</documentRoleForm>
        <domainTag>general-mathematics</domainTag>
        <expertForm>Isometric embedding denotes let $(M,g)$ and $(N,h)$ be Riemannian manifolds. An isometric embedding is a smooth embedding $f : M \\to N$ which preserves the metric in the sense that $g$ is equal to the pullback of $h$ by $f$, i.e. $g = f*h$.</expertForm>
        <pedagogicalForm>Think of isometric embedding as let $(M,g)$ and $(N,h)$ be Riemannian manifolds. An isometric embedding is a smooth embedding $f : M \\to N$ which preserves the metric in the sense that $g$ is equal to the pullback of $h$ by $f$, i.e. $g = f*h$.</pedagogicalForm>
        <sourceProvenance>OntoMathPRO</sourceProvenance>
        <sourceProvenanceNote>Selected from OntoMathPRO English-labeled class inventory to complete the 500 target concept layer.</sourceProvenanceNote>
